        <section>
            <title><text conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termMountingBoardCAP"/> and <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowMatCAP"/> Outer Sizes</title>
            <p>The outer dimensions of a <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termMountingBoard"/> and a <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowMat"/> need to match the <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termFrameSize"/> that could be used to
                frame the art, regardless of whether the art will actually be framed. <text
                    conref="phrasesUsed.dita#reusablePhrases/phraseFrameSizeMeaning"/> When matting
                art, the <text conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termFrameSize"/> will be
                significantly larger than the dimensions of the visible art area in order to allow
                room for a <text conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowBorder"/> around the
                art.</p>
            <p>Here are some typical <text conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termFrameSize"/>s.
                You can often buy precut <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termMountingBoard"/>s and <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowMat"/>s in these sizes. If you
                need a different size, you can cut it yourself from a larger piece of <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termMatboard"/>. </p>
