        <section>
            <title>Inner <text conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowMatCAP"/> Dimensions
                and <text conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowBorderCAP"/> Widths</title>
            <p>Here are some common sizes of precut <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowMat"/>s along with the calculated
                    <text conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowBorder"/>s. The window and
                    <text conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowBorder"/> dimensions are
                approximate. The actual window area is usually slightly smaller than is shown in
                this chart, and the actual <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowBorder"/> is usually slightly
                larger. This slight size difference provides an overlap for art which happens to be
                the same size as the window area. The overlap keeps the art from falling out and
                hides any small areas of the art <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termBackground"/> which should not be
                visible.</p>
            <p>If you need a different size, you can cut the <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowMat"/> yourself.</p>
            <note>In addition to rectangular <text
                    conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowMat"/>s, you can often find
                precut <text conref="termsUsed.dita#reusableTerms/termWindowMat"/>s in other shapes
                such as ovals and circles.</note>
